===Etymology===
From {{inh|nl|dum|solen}}, {{m|dum|suelen}}, {{m|dum|sollen}}, {{m|dum|sullen}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|skulan}}, {{m|odt|sulan}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*skulaną}}. Compare German {{m|de|sollen}}, English {{m|en|shall}}, Danish {{m|da|skulle}}.

===Verb===
{{nl-verb}}

# {{lb|nl|auxiliary|present tense}} [[will]]. Used to form the [[future tense]] of a verb, together with an [[infinitive]].
#: ''Het '''zal''' toch niet werken.''
#:: It '''will''' not work anyway.
#: ''Dat '''zal''' niet gebeuren.''
#:: That '''will''' not happen.
#: '''Note:''' [[gaan]] is also used for the future tense, instead of zullen.
# {{lb|nl|auxiliary|past tense}} [[would]]. Used to form the [[conditional mood]] of a verb, together with an infinitive.
#: ''Het werk '''zou''' nu af zijn geweest als jij je niet had verslapen.''
#:: The work '''would''' have been finished now if you hadn't overslept.
#: ''Dat '''zou''' ik niet doen als ik jou was.''
#:: I '''would''' not do that if I were you.
# {{lb|nl|modal auxiliary}} Used to indicate [[intent]] or [[disposition]] to perform an action in the [[future]]: [[will]], [[shall]], be [[going to]].
#: ''Het '''zou''' vandaag regenen.''
#:: It '''was going to''' rain today.
#: '''''Zal''' ik eerst gaan?''
#:: '''Shall''' I go first?

